title="Abstract Algebra">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Proposition 9.3.5</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-001Z.xml"
addr="ra-001Z"
title="Unique Factorization Domain">Unique Factorization Domain</fr:link>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}=\mathop {\textrm {Frac}}\nolimits (R)]]></fr:tex> be its <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-002B.xml"
addr="ra-002B"
title="Universal property of field of fractions">field of fractions</fr:link>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> be a formal variable. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)\in  R[x]]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)]]></fr:tex> is reducible in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}[x]]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)]]></fr:tex> is reducible in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R[x]]]></fr:tex>. More precisely: if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)=A(x)B(x)]]></fr:tex> for some nonconstant polynomials <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A(x),B(x)\in \mathbb {F}[x]]]></fr:tex>, then there are nonzero elements <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r,s\in \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[rA(x)=a(x)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[sB(x)=b(x)]]></fr:tex> both lie in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R[x]]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)=a(x)b(x)]]></fr:tex> is a factorization in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R[x]]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
